{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"71a4085c-f2cd-4487-b778-38020387fcfe","content":"Here's what's happening and how to fix it:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nEvery `dotnet build` invocation spawns a new process → JIT → loads MSBuild → re-evaluates the project graph. Even when all targets are skipped (no-op), this startup/evaluation overhead costs 2–4 seconds. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild loaded in-process.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**1. Use `dotnet watch build` for the inner loop** (biggest win)\nKeeps the build host process alive and only rebuilds on file changes — eliminates startup overhead entirely:\n```\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n**2. Enable the MSBuild build server**\nReuses a long-lived MSBuild server process across CLI invocations, similar to what VS does. Set this in your shell profile:\n```\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\nThis avoids re-paying JIT and project evaluation costs on every `dotnet build`.\n\n**3. Verify node reuse is not disabled**\nSome CI-oriented configs set `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1`. Make sure this is **not** set in your dev environment — it forces MSBuild to tear down worker nodes after every build.\n\n**4. Add graph-based static evaluation to the project**\nThis speeds up restore/evaluation for the project graph:\n\n```xml\n<!-- In SlowCliBuilds.csproj or a Directory.Build.props -->\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <RestoreUseStaticGraphEvaluation>true</RestoreUseStaticGraphEvaluation>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n## Summary\n\n| Approach | Saves | Effort |\n|---|---|---|\n| `dotnet watch build` | ~2–3s per build (eliminates startup) | None — just change your workflow |\n| `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` | ~1–2s per build (reuses server) | One env var |\n| Verify no `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE=1` | ~0.5–1s (keeps worker nodes) | Check env |\n| `RestoreUseStaticGraphEvaluation` | Faster restore/eval | One line in csproj |\n\nThe **highest-impact, lowest-effort** change is switching to `dotnet watch build` for the edit-build-test cycle. Combined with the MSBuild server env var, CLI builds should feel nearly as fast as VS.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b0b7c039-8967-4b52-b29c-6b25d8b57d84","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` from the CLI is slow for incremental builds (2-4 seconds even with no changes), while Visual Studio rebuilds nearly instantly. They've verified:\n- No analyzers slowing things down\n- Incremental build targets work correctly (targets skip)\n- The project compiles in <500ms\n\nThe overhead is from MSBuild process startup and project graph re-evaluation on every CLI invocation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio uses an in-process MSBuild server that keeps MSBuild warm between builds, avoiding the startup cost. From the CLI, every `dotnet build` invocation starts a new MSBuild process.\n\n\nI can address this with the MSBuild Server, which maintains a persistent MSBuild process between invocations. I can enable it via environment variable or the terminal logger flag (available in .NET 8+), use `dotnet watch` to keep the process alive during development cycles, or manage the server lifecycle directly with `dotnet build-server`. Actually, I need to clarify the MSBuild Server behavior across .NET versions. In .NET 8, it's enabled by default when using the terminal logger, but the real performance win comes from ensuring node reuse isn't disabled—setting `MSBUILDDISABLENODEREUSE` to `0` or leaving it unset lets MSBuild keep worker processes alive between builds. I'm also considering the graph-based build features that can optimize how the project dependencies are evaluated.\n\nThe most practical solution though is recognizing that every CLI invocation pays a startup cost: spinning up a new process, initializing the runtime, loading MSBuild, parsing the project file, and evaluating the graph. Even when targets are skipped, this overhead adds up.\n\nVisual Studio sidesteps this by keeping MSBuild resident in-process and reusing the evaluated project state. For the command line, I can recommend `dotnet watch build` to keep the build host alive between changes, enabling the MSBuild Server with an environment variable for cross-invocation reuse, or adding a project property to use static graph evaluation during restore. Let me put together specific `.csproj` changes and CLI recommendations.","outputTokens":1733,"requestId":"1910:B9052:1327FEF:1587A6A:6A066F05"},"id":"978dec2f-157f-42c7-bbea-d5f07d90f6bb","timestamp":"2026-05-15T00:56:09.823Z","parentId":"ac233f8d-ffcd-4c16-9b47-1447312b000e"}
